metadata.name: The Voyage #52
metadata.description:
The more we explore, the more things we realize there are to be explored. The more questions we find answers to, the more answers we find that require the right questions to be asked.

What is there beyond the edge of knowledge; what was, when things were none?

Will it be our body or our mind to discover that first?

And so The Voyage begins...

* * *

Press R to hide/show cosmic rain (takes a few seconds).
Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Neural Collapse #68
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #261
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden â€œtemplateâ€ canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden â€˜templateâ€™ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #103
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Thread Cascade #57
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free only for 8 hours, for all the holders of "Laser Paintings" and "Beam"!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 10:45 CEST [UTC+2] on the 4th of July 
(example: user holds 3 "Laser Paintings" and 2 "Beam", will be able to mint "Thread Cascade" 5 times)

WARINING: The reserves will expire 8h after the drop! (at 18:45 CEST [UTC+2] on the 4th of July) And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

add ?ratio=n:n to the url to change the piece ratio (replace 'n' with a positive integer, like '?ratio=4:3')

metadata.name: Harmonium #80
metadata.description:
I do not know which to prefer,
The beauty of inflections
Or the beauty of innuendoes,
The blackbird whistling
Or just after.

  Thirteen Ways of Looking at a Blackbird
  Wallace Stevens

Harmonium began as an algorithmic exploration of space filling and curve placement, and grew into a study of the many ways that forms can coexist in a space.

There are three stages to the rendering process:
1. Initial drawing with a placeholder color assignment algorithm
2. Analysis and final color assignment
3. Streamline tapering and conversion to SVG

The final step will typically cause the image to look darker than the previous steps due to the tapering of the streamlines and the vector nature of SVG. I recommend viewing Harmonium outputs on the largest screen you have available.

The final SVG version of the image can be exported by pressing the 'e' key.

*Plotting*

You can disable/enable streamline tapering by pressing the 't' key. Un-tapered exports are intended for plotting on your favorite pen plotter, and include several Inkscape-compatible layer definitions to make plotting different colors possible. (Be sure to disable the background layer.)

The SVG has no dimensions defined so you will need to set the paper dimensions by adjusting the SVG as needed. I will provide additional detail on how to do this in an upcoming blog post. (The short version is to change the page dimensions in Inkscape and set the viewbox width and height to 1.0.)

jpalmer.dev
@jeffpalmer
